{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17477014","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17477014"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:55:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:55:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14112"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14112","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14112"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.78,0.17,0.01,0.04,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6792"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67228"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6792","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6792"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14112"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52680"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"2355"},{"type":"tags","id":"2964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4952"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"4986"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"11624"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11645"},{"type":"tags","id":"11648"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15149"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19126"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39434"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41942"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44196"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67228","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67228"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 14-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his parents. They report that over the past six months, he has been spending increasing amounts of time playing online video games, often staying up late into the night. His grades have dropped significantly, and he has stopped participating in his usual extracurricular activities. He becomes irritable when his parents try to limit his gaming time. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. He is withdrawn during the consultation and minimises his parents\u0027 concerns.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Conduct a comprehensive assessment and provide psychoeducation","Referral to a child psychologist for cognitive behavioural therapy","Recommend complete abstinence from video games","Referral to a child psychiatrist","Prescribe melatonin for sleep regulation"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a 14-year-old boy with symptoms suggestive of gaming disorder, a condition recognised by the World Health Organization. The most appropriate first step in management is to \u003Cstrong\u003Econduct a comprehensive assessment and provide psychoeducation\u003C/strong\u003E. This approach allows the GP to gather more information about the extent of the problem, its impact on the patient\u0027s life, and any underlying factors that may be contributing to the excessive gaming behaviour. It also provides an opportunity to educate the patient and family about gaming addiction and its potential consequences.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrescribing melatonin\u003C/strong\u003E for sleep regulation, while potentially helpful for addressing sleep disturbances, does not address the core issue of gaming addiction and should not be the first step in management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferring to a child psychiatrist\u003C/strong\u003E may be necessary in severe cases or if there are comorbid mental health conditions, but it is not typically the first step. The GP can initiate management and refer later if needed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERecommending complete abstinence from video games\u003C/strong\u003E is likely to be met with resistance and may not be necessary or realistic. A more balanced approach involving moderation and setting healthy limits is often more effective.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferral to a psychologist for cognitive behavioural therapy\u003C/strong\u003E would likely prove beneficial for this patient, and may be a part of his management plan. However, a referral would not be made until after a comprehensive assessment is performed, as this may detect other co-morbidities (i.e. depression) that also require treatment. Moreover, lifestyle changes (i.e. finding strategies to reduce gaming time) and parental support may be sufficient in ameloriating his symptoms, and these should be trialled initially.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter conducting a comprehensive assessment and providing psychoeducation, the next steps would typically involve collaborative goal-setting with the patient and family, developing strategies to reduce gaming time, encouraging alternative activities, and addressing any underlying issues (e.g., anxiety, depression) that may be contributing to the excessive gaming behaviour. Regular follow-up appointments would be important to monitor progress and adjust the management plan as needed.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Gaming disorder is characterised by impaired control over gaming, increasing priority given to gaming over other activities, and continuation of gaming despite negative consequences.","Initial GP management of gaming addiction involves a comprehensive assessment, education, and collaborative goal-setting with the patient and family.","Referral to mental health services may be necessary for severe cases or when there are comorbid mental health conditions."],"references":["Loton D, Lubman DI. Just one more level: Identifying and addressing internet gaming disorder within primary care. Aust Fam Physician 2016; 45:48-52. https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2016/january-february/just-one-more-level-identifying-and-addressing-int"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52680"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14112"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52680","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52680"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-04T08:58:56+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-10T16:07:05+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6792"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67228"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":